ENTRY 1 - FIRST IMPRESSION: Table s8_time_allocation shows respondent allocations (%) of professional time across four activities. First reaction: useful as-is.

ENTRY 2 - SURVEY CHECK: Found question S8 in survey: 'Approximately what percentage of your professional time is spent performing each of the following activities?' Items: Treating/Managing patients; Performing academic functions (e.g., teaching, publishing); Participating in clinical research; Performing other functions. Labels in the table match the survey text: yes. Variable types are numeric percentage ranges (0-100).

ENTRY 3 - ANALYST LENS: If I were analyzing this, I would want the table to explicitly note these are percentages that should sum to 100 and show standard summary stats (mean/median/std). I also want row metadata fields present for downstream processing (isNet, netComponents, indent). No NETs, T2B, or splits are appropriate because these are continuous % allocations across distinct activities. This is not a scale requiring top/bottom box. The question is core to sample characterization and should not be excluded.

ENTRY 4 - DECISION: Final: pass through with small clarifications. Changes: (1) Clarified table title to note values are percentages and sum to 100 and that mean/median/std dev are expected; (2) Added required row metadata fields (isNet=false, netComponents=[], indent=0) for each row. No NET rows, no splits, not excluded, not derived. sourceTableId left empty since not derived.
Implementation notes: Kept original variable names (S8r1-S8r4) unchanged. filterValue left empty because these are continuous numeric variables. Confidence in decisions: high.
ENTRY 1 - FIRST IMPRESSION: Table s12 shows respondent counts of patients by time since event (numeric counts). First reaction: useful as-is (needs only technical completion).

ENTRY 2 - SURVEY CHECK: Found question in survey S12: 'Of those, how many patients have had an event (MI, CAD, coronary revascularization, stent placement, etc.)' with four numeric buckets (Over 5 years ago; Within the last 3-5 years; Within the last 1-2 years; Within the last year). Labels in the input table match the survey wording exactly: yes.

ENTRY 3 - ANALYST LENS: As an analyst I would want the table to show means (and possibly distributions) of counts per bucket. I considered adding a NET (total patients with event = sum of the four buckets) because analysts often want the total; however the instructions include a critical constraint to never invent variable names (SPSS column names) that aren't in the input. Creating a multi-variable NET would require inventing a new variable name, so I did not add it here. If the project allows derived/net variables with a standard naming convention, we can add a NET row later using netComponents referencing S12r1..S12r4.

ENTRY 4 - DECISION: Final: pass through content but complete required structure. Changes: added required fields for each row (isNet=false, netComponents=[], indent=0) and table-level metadata (sourceTableId, isDerived, exclude, excludeReason). No label edits, no splits, no T2B (not a scale), not excluded.
Technical note: Rows are numeric ranges (counts). filterValue intentionally left empty because these are numeric open-end fields, not categorical codes.
